messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Summary
- Base router mount: app.use('/users', userRoutes) in index.js
- Routes defined in routes/userRoutes.js (all use router.post(...))

Full endpoint paths and allowed methods
1) Path: /users/signin
   - All HTTP methods allowed: false
   - HEAD: false
   - POST: true
   - OPTIONS: true
   - TRACE: false
   - GET: false
   - PUT: false
   - DELETE: false
   - PATCH: false

2) Path: /users/signup
   - All HTTP methods allowed: false
   - HEAD: false
   - POST: true
   - OPTIONS: true
   - TRACE: false
   - GET: false
   - PUT: false
   - DELETE: false
   - PATCH: false

3) Path: /users/forgot
   - All HTTP methods allowed: false
   - HEAD: false
   - POST: true
   - OPTIONS: true
   - TRACE: false
   - GET: false
   - PUT: false
   - DELETE: false
   - PATCH: false

4) Path: /users/reset
   - All HTTP methods allowed: false
   - HEAD: false
   - POST: true
   - OPTIONS: true
   - TRACE: false
   - GET: false
   - PUT: false
   - DELETE: false
   - PATCH: false

Explanation / reasoning
- index.js mounts the router at the '/users' prefix: app.use('/users', userRoutes). Therefore each route in routes/userRoutes.js is prefixed with /users.
- routes/userRoutes.js defines four routes and uses router.post(...) for each: '/signin', '/signup', '/forgot', '/reset'. That yields the four full paths above, all accepting POST.
- There are no router.get, router.put, router.delete, router.patch, or router.options handlers in the userRoutes file, so GET/PUT/DELETE/PATCH/TRACE are not implemented for these endpoints in the code.
- HEAD is only automatically supported by Express for routes that have GET handlers. Because these endpoints only define POST handlers, HEAD is not provided by the application code for them.
- OPTIONS: The application registers the CORS middleware globally with app.use(cors()) in index.js. The cors() middleware handles CORS preflight requests (OPTIONS) automatically, so OPTIONS requests will be handled (true) for these endpoints based on the code. 
- TRACE: there is no TRACE handler and Express does not implement TRACE by default, so TRACE is false.
- "All HTTP methods acceptable" is false because only specific methods are implemented (POST, and OPTIONS via CORS middleware).
